Planning:

We need the following threads:
ui
audio
general processing
(possibly an autosave thread)

slint automatically generates a separate ui thread, so we can keep general processing on the main thread, and have a separate thread for audio, controlled by an AudioController class. (which wraps notifies).

ui and general can wait, i.e. can allocate memory and run locks.
audio thread must be real time, so cannot allocate memory during play loops (but can do so outside of these loops).

How to manage state:

- copies to keep state in sync:
  - multi write: write to all states every time they change
  - replace:
    - copy from: copy from core state before any major actions (could be costly)
    - copy to: copy to substates after every update block
  - sync:
    - align at critical points.

Multi write seems the best option.
Probably best done via a central state object, whose class manages multi way updates.
However, this may make it difficult to avoid locks in the audio thread. Could investigate whether try_lock would resolve this.

State required:
Audio:
We need io from busses in order to plot volumes + spectrographs
We need the routing of midi generators, audio generators, midi in, audio in, and audio out.
Each generator will require state. For programmatic state (vs midi in and audio in) we can get away with taking a copy of the state on play.

Ideal solution:
Main thread creates a slint based Data Model containing
Output Generators (Audio / Midi)

- Tracks
- Regions (can audio and midi be mixed?)
  - Midi
    - Sequence
    - Pattern
  - Audio
    - Sequence
    - Pattern
- Busses
- FX
- Routing
  - midi outputs to audio generators
  - audio generators to busses
  - audio generators to FX
  - buss to stereo out
  - (inputs to generators / recorders)
- General / Settings

Note, inputs/recording are too complicated right now. Ignore this and build a good tracker.

The audio thread, on the other hand, will maintain a set of owned buffers containing audio data for each of these structures.
TBD whether to trigger a rebuild of this structure on hitting play, or based on updates to the Structure definition. Probably the latter, managed with notifications to an audio side wiring manager
In addition, each Buss will expose a metrics section containing atomic variables for metric values - initally left and right channel value.

Visualisers can than calculate a display value from this by reading it on the graphics event loop. Additional metrics may be calculated by other threads.
